              <div class="all hidden" style="display:none" >
                1. It reminds me the &quot;history and philosophy of geography&quot; class during my first year of PHD.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>2. Unfortunately looks like the question &quot;what is geography&quot; still do not have an answer most people agree on, though Mackinder and others have tried to give the definition and outline the scope of geography several times.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>3. It is still hard to find a solid link between physical and human geography, though I tried to love Mackinder's explanation about the relationship between them. Or maybe it is just because I am working on a field which is too narrow.<div style="padding-bottom:1em;"></div>4. Looks like the idea in this chapter has been adopted for structuring introductory geography courses for a long time.
